>What are his sleeping habits like?
For a good while they were absolutely godawful. He was terrified of dying in his sleep, he'd have constant night terrors and would go as far as to hurt himself at times. However, he's much better if someone is there with him, holding his hand while he sleeps.
When he is better, he's a really heavy sleeper. You can poke at his cheeks as much as you want, though he did start sucking down on a finger once.
He's proud that he doesn't usually get groggy when he wakes up.
>What would he wear to bed?
On his own he isn't too picky about what he wears to bed, but he's the sort that would make personalized matching themed pajamas sets.
>What would your morning routine look like with him?
Since he got isekai'd and started work as a butler, he's made sure to wake up really early and do his stretches, he's the sort that would get you into it too, but maybe if you're too sleepy he'll quietly slip out instead.
While washing up, he'll practice his facial expressions in the mirror and gives himself little pep talks sometimes.
He's the type that would say breakfast is meant to be eaten together.
>Does he drink coffee? If not what kind do you think he would like?
He doesn't seem like he'd be too fussed about it, though before getting transferred he might have been more of an energy drink sort of guy. The last drink he had before getting isekai'd was hot cocoa made by his mom.
After getting isekai'd he got into tea by way of another character, Ram, and would steal from her secret tea stash on occassion.

In traditional indigenous Ainu marriages, People who marry in their own villages are all called uiriwak, ‘blood relations,’ ‘brethren,’ but those who marry OUTSIDE their villages are called uiritak, i.e. ‘relation taken away,’ or ‘distant relations,’ ‘brethren brought in.’

Soon after marriage the bridegroom makes a knife sheath, a spoon, a shuttle and weaving loom, and presents them to his bride. This little ceremony is called mat-eikara, i.e. ‘making my wife.’ The bride then makes a girdle, a pair of leggings, a necklace, and a head-dress, which she presents to her husband; this is called hoku eikara, i.e. ‘making my husband.’

Chinese BL novels. Often associated with long-haired swordfighting pretty boys, however there's a myriad of different genres available, from wuxia and xianxia to modern crime thrillers to historical political dramas.

>Where do I start?
Check out Mo Xiang Tong Xiu's novels (The Scum Villain's Self-Saving System, Grandmaster of Demonic Cultivation, Heaven Official's Blessing) for the aforementioned sword boys.
Other popular authors are Priest, Meatbun Doesn't Eat Meat, and Meng Xi Shi.
